  "doc_id": "9062",
  "text": "Data concerning mortality trends are scarce in the literature. In England and Wales from 1968 to 2008, 878 deaths due to hypersensitivity pneumonitis were reported and increased in time from a first period (1968) (1969) (1970) (1971) (1972) ) to a later period (2005) (2006) (2007) (2008) . Mortality was higher in men and with increasing age [CITATION_1] . In the recent Danish cohort, 5-year survival in the hypersensitivity pneumonitis group was 93% [15 && ]. An interesting finding is that depending on the causative antigen, the prognosis seems to differ as there are some data suggesting that bird fancier's hypersensitivity pneumonitis might have a worse prognosis than farmer's lung. This might be because of the fact that patients with established fibrosis on HRCT and/or surgical lung biopsy have a poorer prognosis [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
